SIMPLE: infix
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Infix
<hw>In*fix"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Infixed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Infixing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>infixus</ets>, p. p of
<ets>infigere</ets> to infix; pref. <ets>in-</ets> in +
<ets>figere</ets> to fix: cf. F. <ets>infixer</ets>. See
<er>Fix</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To set; to fasten or fix by
piercing or thrusting in; <as>as, to <ex>infix</ex> a sting, spear, or
dart</as>.</def> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fatal dart a ready passage found,⟦br⟧
And deep within her heart <qex>infixed</qex> the wound.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To implant or fix; to instill; to inculcate, as
principles, thoughts, or instructions; <as>as, to <ex>infix</ex> good
principles in the mind, or ideas in the memory</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Infix</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Infix
<hw>In"fix</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something
infixed.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Welsford.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Grammar)</fld> <def>An element that is inserted
into the body of an elemt which it threby modifies, as a letter within a
word.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>infix notation</ent>⟦br⟧
